HOUSE BILL No. 1428
A BILL FOR AN ACT to amend the Indiana Code concerning
health.
Be it enacted by the General Assembly of the State of Indiana:
1 SECTION 1. IC 16-18-2-235 IS AMENDED TO READ AS
2 FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE UPON PASSAGE]: Sec. 235. "Minor", for
3 purposes of IC 16-19-3-4.7 and IC 16-36, means an individual who is
4 less than eighteen (18) years of age.
5 SECTION 2. IC 16-19-3-4.7 IS ADDED TO THE INDIANA CODE
6 AS A NEW SECTION TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
7 UPON PASSAGE]: Sec. 4.7. (a) As used in this section, "lifeguard"
8 refers to an individual who holds a nationally recognized
9 certification in lifeguard training that is responsible for supervising
10 swimming activities and ensuring water safety.
11 (b) As used in this section, "pool" means a structure, basin,
12 chamber, or tank containing an artificial body of water for
13 swimming, bathing, relaxation, or recreational use that has a
14 surface area of two thousand (2,000) square feet or more.
15 (c) As used in this section, "senior neighborhood" means a
16 residential community where occupancy is restricted to individuals
17 who are at least fifty-five (55) years of age.
2026 IN 1428—LS 6950/DI 104

2
1 (d) Except as provided in subsection (e), a senior neighborhood
2 may not be required to have a lifeguard on duty at the
3 neighborhood's pool if the following conditions are met:
4 (1) The pool is not deeper than six (6) feet in any section of the
5 pool.
6 (2) The pool does not have a diving board, diving well, or
7 water slide.
8 (e) If a senior neighborhood decides to hold visiting hours to
9 allow visiting minors to swim in the pool, the senior neighborhood
10 must have a lifeguard on duty during the hours of the day
11 designated by the senior community's governing board to permit
12 visiting minors to use the pool. A minor may not use the senior
13 neighborhood pool outside of the designated visiting hours. The
14 senior neighborhood shall adopt and enforce rules to ensure
15 compliance with this subsection.
16 (f) A senior neighborhood that decides not to employ a lifeguard
17 for the pool and establishes pool visiting hours for minors as
18 allowed under this section shall post clear and conspicuous signage
19 at each pool entrance that states the following:
20 "No lifeguard on duty-swim at your own risk".
21 "Children under 18 are allowed at the pool during visiting
22 hours only".
23 The senior neighborhood shall ensure that the signage is
24 maintained in good condition and comply with any applicable state
25 or local regulations.
26 (g) A senior neighborhood that decides not to employ a lifeguard
27 for the pool and not to establish pool visiting hours for minors shall
28 post clear and conspicuous signage at each pool entrance that
29 states the following:
30 "No lifeguard on duty- swim at your own risk".
31 "Children under 18 are not allowed at the pool".
32 The senior neighborhood shall ensure that the signage is
33 maintained in good condition and comply with any applicable state
34 or local regulations.
35 (h) A senior neighborhood shall notify residents concerning the
36 rules regarding pool use, including the visiting hours, if any, in
37 which a minor may use the pool.
38 (i) The state department may assess a senior neighborhood a
39 fine of one thousand dollars ($1,000) per violation of this section.
40 SECTION 3. [EFFECTIVE UPON PASSAGE] (a) The Indiana
41 department of health shall amend 410 IAC 6-2.1 to conform with
42 this act. The Indiana department of health shall inform local health
